PanRes DataBase Generation

Patrick Munk

A number of ARG databases include genes of relevance when considering bacterial AMR.

But not all these databases are soly acquired resistance genes.

Let us come up with a method for screening genes for inclusion. We will run GeneAssimilatoR a number of rounds and use apply filtering depending on our findigs.

Preparation


library(tidyverse)

Let us first start an initial round here. This will help us make it reproducible and the geneAssimilatoR output can then help us refine the gene collection for subsequent rounds.

#system2("GeneAssimilatoR.R --dbdir databases --outputdir panresdb_test2 --prefix tmp")
system2("Rscript", "GeneAssimilatoR.R --dbdir databases --outputdir panresdb_round1 --prefix pan")

Lower percentage in clusters than in unique variants indicate that a given database has higher than average redundancy. I guess ResFinder has fewer families, but a large number of variants for those genes.

Of all the variants in the dataset, how many them fall within 90% identity clusters of a ResFinder variant?

MEGARes Data Curation

What are the sequences that uniquely show up in MEGARES


GenesUniqueToDatabase = function(master_table, db_name) {
  master_table = master_table %>% 
  select(userGeneName, database) %>% 
  table %>% 
  as.data.frame.matrix %>% 
  as_tibble(rownames = "userGeneName")

gene_names = master_table %>% 
  mutate(numDbs = rowSums(master_table %>% 
                            select(-1))) %>% 
  mutate(inDb = get(db_name) == 1) %>%
  filter(inDb == T) %>%
  filter(numDbs == 1) %>%
  pull(userGeneName)
return(gene_names)
}

uniqueMegaresGenes = GenesUniqueToDatabase(prdat, "megares_genes") # 1410
uniqueResFinderGenes = GenesUniqueToDatabase(prdat, "resfinder_genes") # Just 14

These are the gene variants that uniquly show up in ResFinder

Relatively few unique names we have to review. Let os focus on the RequiresSNPConfirmation These are the genes that the authors feel need SNP data to be meaningful. Presence/absence/acquisition is not enough

megaSubset = megaSubset %>%
  filter(Note == "RequiresSNPConfirmation")

uniqueMegaResnames = megaSubset %>% 
  filter(Note == "RequiresSNPConfirmation") %>% 
  select(ResName, ResType, Descript) %>% 
  unique()

uniqueMegaResnames

We could just throw out everything with RequiresSNPConfirmation.

I assume the remaining will be more in line with what is in the other databases (acquired genes) But Frank did not think e.g.efflux pumps should be excluded.

Let us find a combination of words of genes that we dont want in our data. This will give us the subset of genes with the RequiresSNPConfirmation tag that we want to retain.


filt1 = megaSubset[grep("_mutant", megaSubset$fa_name),] %>% pull(ResName)
filt2 = megaSubset[grep("_mutation", megaSubset$fa_name),] %>% pull(ResName)
filt3 = megaSubset[grep("_regulator", megaSubset$fa_name),] %>% pull(ResName)
filt4 = megaSubset[grep("_repressor", megaSubset$fa_name),] %>% pull(ResName) 
filt5 = megaSubset[grep("_promoter", megaSubset$fa_name),] %>% pull(ResName) 
filt6 = megaSubset[grep("resistant_", megaSubset$fa_name),] %>% pull(ResName) 
filt7 = megaSubset[grep("Mutant_", megaSubset$fa_name),] %>% pull(ResName) 
  
# Now what is left?
megaGenesRemain = megaSubset %>%
  filter(!ResName %in% c(filt1,filt2,filt3,filt4,filt5,filt6, filt7)) %>%

  unique()
